{{Infobox scholar|name = Sadakichi Kita (喜田 貞吉)|image = Sadakichi Kita.JPG|image_size =|image_caption =|native_name = 喜田 貞吉|birth_date = {{ill|July 11, 1871|ja|1871年7月11日}} ({{ill|Meiji 4|ja|明治4年}} {{ill|May 24 (lunar calendar)|ja|5月24日 (旧暦)}})|birth_place = {{JPN}} {{ill|Kushibuchi Village, Naka District, Awa Province|ja|阿波国那賀郡櫛淵村}} (now {{ill|Komatsushima City, Tokushima Prefecture|ja|徳島県小松島市}})|death_date = {{ill|July 3, 1939|ja|1939年7月3日}} ({{ill|Showa 14|ja|昭和14年}})|death_place = {{JPN}} {{ill|Sendai City, Miyagi Prefecture|ja|宮城県仙台市}}|nationality = {{JPN}}|alma_mater = {{ill|Tokyo Imperial University, Faculty of Letters|ja|帝国大学文科大学}}|field = {{ill|History|ja|歴史学}}|institutions = {{ill|Tokyo Imperial University|ja|東京帝国大学}}, {{ill|Kyoto Imperial University|ja|京都帝国大学}}, {{ill|Tohoku Imperial University|ja|東北帝国大学}}|known_for = Proposing numerous hypotheses on the formation of the Japanese ethnic group through the lenses of history and archaeology}}'''Sadakichi Kita''' (喜田 貞吉, July 11, 1871 – July 3, 1939) was a pre-World War II Japanese historian and literary scholar. He integrated {{ill|archaeology|ja|考古学}} and {{ill|folklore studies|ja|民俗学}} into his academic research.== Career ==Sadakichi Kita was born into a farming family in {{ill|Kushibuchi Village, Awa Province|ja|阿波国那賀郡櫛淵村}} (present-day {{ill|Komatsushima City, Tokushima Prefecture|ja|徳島県小松島市}}). After graduating from local schools, he advanced to {{ill|Tokushima Junior High School|ja|徳島中学校}}, followed by {{ill|Third High School (Old System)|ja|第三高等学校 (旧制)}}. In 1893, at the age of 23, he enrolled in the Faculty of Letters at {{ill|Tokyo Imperial University|ja|帝国大学}}, where he studied history. Among his classmates were {{ill|Ginzō Uchida|ja|内田銀蔵}} and {{ill|Katsumi Kuroita|ja|黒板勝美}}. After graduating in 1896 from the Department of National History, he continued his postgraduate studies under scholars such as {{ill|Kumazo Tsuboi|ja|坪井九馬三}}, focusing on "the historical geography of Japan."During his time as a lecturer at the university, Kita published textbooks such as "Japanese Geography" and "Foreign Geography" (co-authored with {{ill|Shigetomo Kōda|ja|幸田成友}}). In 1909, he earned a {{ill|Doctorate in Literature|ja|文学博士}} for his research on {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京}} and the {{ill|Reconstruction debate of Hōryū-ji|ja|法隆寺再建論争}}. Later, his involvement in writing {{ill|national textbooks|ja|国定教科書}} for elementary schools led to controversy. In 1911, his decision to present both the {{ill|Northern Court|ja|北朝}} and {{ill|Southern Court|ja|南朝}} during the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代}} in textbooks resulted in public backlash, eventually leading to his temporary suspension.From 1913, Kita served as a lecturer at {{ill|Kyoto Imperial University|ja|京都帝国大学}} and became a professor there in 1920. By 1924, he had joined {{ill|Tohoku Imperial University|ja|東北帝国大学}}. There, he laid the foundation for the study of ancient Japanese history and archaeology.== Contributions to Research ==Kita proposed independent theories on the formation of the Japanese ethnic group and explored the history of Japan's origins through archaeological and historical studies. One notable hypothesis suggested that people creating {{ill|Jōmon pottery|ja|縄文土器}} continued to live in Eastern Japan until the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代}}, sparking the {{ill|Minerva Debate|ja|ミネルヴァ論争}}.== Works ===== Major Publications ===* ''Japanese Geography'' (1899)* ''Hōryū-ji and Its Reconstruction Debate'' (1910)* ''Stories of Japanese History'' (1928)* ''Studies on Buraku Issues'' (1968)== Legacy ==Kita's pioneering studies bridged history and archaeology, influencing subsequent generations of scholars. His work on Japanese folklore and geographical history remains integral to the understanding of Japan's cultural heritage.== References ==* {{Cite book|author=Eiji Oguma|title=The Myth of a Homogeneous Nation|year=1995}}* {{Cite journal|author=Daisuke Itō|title=Archival Materials on Sadakichi Kita|journal=Tohoku Asian Studies}}== External Links ==* [http://www.example.com Biography of Sadakichi Kita] ]][[Category:Japanese historians]]]][[Category:19th-century scholars]]]][[Category:20th-century scholars]]]][[Category:People from Tokushima Prefecture]]]][[Category:1871 births]]]][[Category:1939 deaths]]]][[Category:pp]]]][[category:Kida Sadakichi]]]][[Category:pp]]]][[Category:pp]]]][[category:Kida Sadakichi]]]][[Category:pp]]]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]]
