From 1913, Kita served as a lecturer at {{ill|Kyoto Imperial University|ja|京都帝国大学|12=draft|12=draft}} and became a professor there in 1920. By 1924, he had joined {{ill|Tohoku Imperial University|ja|東北帝国大学|12=draft|12=draft}}. There, he laid the foundation for the study of ancient Japanese history and archaeology.

== Contributions to Research ==

Kita proposed independent theories on the formation of the Japanese ethnic group and explored the history of Japan's origins through archaeological and historical studies. One notable hypothesis suggested that people creating {{ill|Jōmon pottery|ja|縄文土器|12=draft|12=draft}} continued to live in Eastern Japan until the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, sparking the {{ill|Minerva Debate|ja|ミネルヴァ論争|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Works ==
=== Major Publications ===
* ''Japanese Geography'' (1899)
* ''Hōryū-ji and Its Reconstruction Debate'' (1910)
* ''Stories of Japanese History'' (1928)
* ''Studies on Buraku Issues'' (1968)

== Legacy ==
Kita's pioneering studies bridged history and archaeology, influencing subsequent generations of scholars. His work on Japanese folklore and geographical history remains integral to the understanding of Japan's cultural heritage.

== References ==
* {{Cite book|author=Eiji Oguma|title=The Myth of a Homogeneous Nation|year=1995}}
* {{Cite journal|author=Daisuke Itō|title=Archival Materials on Sadakichi Kita|journal=Tohoku Asian Studies}}

